Taken on Long Distance trips every year with never any failures or problems.

1985 BMW K100RT

Last Year Drove her across Canada. When I got home I decided to repaint her.
One thing led to another and I decided to do every upgrade possible plus some.
I rebuild the drive-shaft, adjusted the lifters, rebuilt all the brakes and added new stainless steel brake lines. Rebuilt the rear "Worx" Shock. Added heat reflective material everywhere needed.
Mailed out the injectors and had them cleaned. Painted the frame, started to work on body, then moved and lost interest. My kid takes up all my time now.

Brand new front tire with zero miles, rear tire has 400 miles, newly recovered and re-padded with gel inserts Corbin seat, new battery last year. Have two gas tanks, two sets of body panels, lights, everything. New kickstand and upgraded stater from K1100 bike.

Currently she is sitting as in first pic.

I have over $2000 in extra parts, replacement upgrades, and new upgrades.
- such as progressive shocks for the front, all new rubber for everything, new mounts and screws, new Bosch upgraded starter and wiring kit, larger windshield, etc, any possible upgrade and improvement that can ever be done is in two large containers in my garage. Have another large box or two of extra parts as well.

All parts taken off have been cleaned and labeled and put in bags so i could easily reinstall them.

I've personally got over $5500 in this bike.

My loss your gain for a little elbow grease putting her back together. If I had the time and the desire to ride again, I'd say maybe two weekends at best to get her to show condition.

Asking $2200 for everything. (price Lowered from $3500 11/9/14)
Price is Firm! Will not ever go lower, so please do not waste my time with any other cash offer.

May take full or partial + Cash trades on Jeep CJ or Wrangler, things thatgoboom, Nice 2000 and up Pop Up Camper, silver.

title: For Sale:  KSG PATRIOT BROWN GEN2 Keltec Shotgun Pump
location: North Carolina, North Carolina, United States
postcontent: New production Gen 2 unfired direct from the factory Kel Tec KSG Patriot Brown 12 shot 12 gauge shot gun. This is serious fire power. From the factory: The KSG is our first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape and design are similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9lbs and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1" overall length and an 18.5" cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 6 rounds of 12 gage 3" shells each, for a total capacity of 6+6+1 (7 per tube if using 2-3/4" shells). The simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard. The lever can be positioned in the center detent in order to easily clear the chamber without feeding another round from either magazine. A cross bolt style safety blocks the sear, and the pump release lever is located in front of the trigger guard. The pump includes an under Picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, or a light or laser. The included top Picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil

title: For Sale:  Discrepencies between Federal/State definitions of 'Firearm'
postcontent:
RCW 9.41.010 - "Terms Defined" lists the following:
(9) "Firearm" means a weapon or device from which a projectile or projectiles may be fired by an explosive such as gunpowder.

This doesn't seem to cover receivers or frames, so looks like private sales are still OK for stripped receivers, or frame + Parts kit (barrel, slide, recoil spring) or AR lower receiver + parts kit (upper, bolt carrier, charging handle), etc without a background check. 

Example
1. Sell a handgun barrel and lower separately.
2. Sell a rifle upper and lower receivers separately.


For reference, here is the federal definition of "firearm" according to 18 U.S. Code § 921 (see section B)
(3) The term “firearm” means
(A) any weapon (including a starter
gun) which will or is designed to or may readily be converted to expel a
projectile by the action of an explosive;
[b]
(B) the frame or receiver of any such weapon;
(C) any firearm muffler or firearm silencer; or
(D) any destructive device. Such term does not include an antique firearm
